headline: Retail earnings, housing data, FOMC minutes: What to Watch
summary: Market Domination Overtime host Josh Lipton takes a look at the top stories for investors to watch next week, starting Monday, Aug. 18. Several earnings reports are on deck, including from Home Depot (HD) on Tuesday, Lowe's (LOW) and Target (TGT) on Wednesday, Walmart (WMT) and Alibaba (BABA) on Thursday, and more. On Monday, the Homebuilder Confidence Index for August will be released in the morning, giving economists fresh insight into the state of the housing market. The Federal Reserve will release its meeting minutes from the July FOMC meeting on Wednesday at 2 p.m. To watch more expert insights and analysis on the latest market action, check out more Market Domination Overtime.

headline: Target and Ulta mutually agree not to renew partnership launched in 2021
summary: Target and Ulta Beauty are parting ways, ending a partnership launched in 2021 that created in-store shops filled with beauty products at hundreds of the discounter's stores.  Until then, the Ulta Beauty experience at Target will continue in Target stores and on Target.com, the release said.  Ulta is currently in 600 of Target's roughly 1,980 stores, according to a Target spokesperson.

headline: Standard Chartered, Joby, Target downgrade: Trending Tickers
summary: Standard Chartered (STAN.L) shares slumped after Republican Congresswoman Elise Stefanik called for an investigation into allegations it enabled "illicit payments to known terrorists." In a statement, the bank says, "The underlying allegations – including the claim that there are $9.6 billion in unlawful transactions – are entirely false and have been rejected by the US courts multiple times." Joby Aviation (JOBY) reports a successful piloted flight between two US airports. Bank of America analysts downgrade Target (TGT) to Underperform, citing a "deteriorating" longterm outlook.
